<ArticleLayout
  title="Washing Machine and Dryer Space: What to Measure Before Buying Storage"
  description="Before buying storage around a washing machine or dryer, check machine width, depth, door clearance, hose access, dryer ventilation, power points and maintenance space."
  category="Laundry"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/laundry.webp"
  imageAlt="A practical laundry room with warm finishes, baskets and tidy everyday storage"
>
  <p>
    The space around a washing machine or dryer can look like an easy storage
    opportunity.
  </p>
  <p>
    There may be a gap beside the machine, space above a front loader, a wall behind
    the laundry tub, a narrow area near the dryer, or a corner that seems suitable for
    shelves, baskets, a slim trolley or an over-machine unit. But laundry appliances
    need clearance, access and airflow. Storage that looks useful can quickly become a
    problem if it blocks doors, lids, hoses, taps, filters, vents or power points.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying storage for the washing machine or dryer area, it is worth measuring
    the appliance space properly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Good appliance-area storage should make laundry easier without making the machines
    harder to use, clean, inspect or maintain.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader laundry planning, see our main guide:
    <a href="/guides/laundry-storage-what-to-measure-and-check-before-you-buy/">
      Laundry Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with the real appliance-area problem</h2>
  <p>
    Before buying storage, work out what is actually causing the laundry to feel
    crowded.
  </p>
  <p>The problem may be:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>detergent sitting on top of the machine</li>
    <li>baskets blocking the washing machine door</li>
    <li>a narrow gap beside the appliance collecting clutter</li>
    <li>nowhere to store pegs, cloths or stain removers</li>
    <li>dryer access being blocked by baskets or shelves</li>
    <li>hoses and taps reducing usable space</li>
    <li>a top-loader lid hitting storage above it</li>
    <li>a front-loader door opening into a narrow walkway</li>
    <li>cleaning products stored too close to heat or moisture</li>
    <li>no clear place for laundry items used every week</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Different problems need different storage choices.
  </p>
  <p>
    If detergent is the issue, a small shelf or trolley may help. If baskets block
    the machine, the basket system needs attention first. If drying is the problem,
    storage around the machine may not solve it.
  </p>
  <p>
    For tight rooms, cupboards and apartment laundries, see:
    <a href="/guides/small-laundry-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-organisers/">
      Small Laundry Storage: What to Check Before Buying Organisers</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The first step is to measure the appliance area and identify what needs to stay
    accessible.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the washing machine first</h2>
  <p>
    The washing machine usually controls the laundry layout.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying any nearby storage, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>machine width</li>
    <li>machine depth</li>
    <li>machine height</li>
    <li>space beside the machine</li>
    <li>space above the machine</li>
    <li>space behind the machine</li>
    <li>tap position</li>
    <li>hose position</li>
    <li>power point position</li>
    <li>door or lid clearance</li>
    <li>whether the machine moves during use</li>
    <li>access for cleaning and maintenance</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Measure the actual machine, not just the laundry opening. Washing machines can be
    deeper than they look once hoses, doors and handles are considered.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage should not be pushed so tightly around the machine that hoses are crowded,
    taps are blocked or the appliance becomes hard to move when needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Check top-loader lid clearance</h2>
  <p>
    Top-loading washing machines need clear space above the machine.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying shelves, racks or over-machine storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>how high the lid opens</li>
    <li>whether the lid can stay open</li>
    <li>whether shelves block loading and unloading</li>
    <li>whether detergent bottles stored above are easy to reach</li>
    <li>whether items could fall into the machine</li>
    <li>whether the storage makes the machine awkward to use</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A shelf above a top loader may look useful, but it can become frustrating if it
    prevents the lid from opening fully.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the machine is a top loader, vertical storage needs extra care.
  </p>

  <h2>Check front-loader door clearance</h2>
  <p>
    Front-loading washing machines need clear space in front.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying baskets, hampers, shelves or trolleys, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>how far the door opens</li>
    <li>whether the door opens left or right</li>
    <li>whether a basket can sit nearby without blocking access</li>
    <li>whether the walkway remains clear</li>
    <li>whether washing can be loaded and unloaded comfortably</li>
    <li>whether a pedestal, shelf or bench changes access</li>
    <li>whether the machine filter or lower panel remains reachable if applicable</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A basket or sorter that fits in the laundry may still be wrong if it blocks the
    front-loader door.
  </p>
  <p>
    For basket planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/laundry-basket-storage-what-to-sort-before-buying-hampers-or-sorters/">
      Laundry Basket Storage: What to Sort Before Buying Hampers or Sorters</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Check dryer clearance and ventilation</h2>
  <p>
    Dryer space needs careful planning.
  </p>
  <p>Before adding shelves, baskets or storage around a dryer, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>dryer width</li>
    <li>dryer depth</li>
    <li>dryer height</li>
    <li>door swing</li>
    <li>power point access</li>
    <li>ventilation requirements</li>
    <li>space around vents</li>
    <li>access for cleaning and maintenance</li>
    <li>whether heat or moisture may affect nearby storage</li>
    <li>whether manufacturer guidance limits placement</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not block vents, airflow or access points.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide does not provide dryer installation advice. Follow the appliance
    manufacturer's guidance for clearance, ventilation, stacking and placement.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage around a dryer should be conservative. If a shelf, basket or rack makes
    ventilation or access worse, it is not the right storage choice.
  </p>

  <h2>Be cautious with stacked appliances</h2>
  <p>
    Stacked washing machines and dryers can save space, but they need proper setup.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage for a stacked appliance area, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>appliance manufacturer guidance</li>
    <li>whether stacking is suitable for those models</li>
    <li>whether a proper stacking kit is required</li>
    <li>height of the full setup</li>
    <li>reach to controls</li>
    <li>dryer door access</li>
    <li>ventilation</li>
    <li>service access</li>
    <li>surrounding clearance</li>
    <li>whether nearby shelves make access harder</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not assume any dryer can be safely stacked on any washing machine.
  </p>
  <p>
    If stacking is being considered, follow manufacturer instructions and use appropriate
    installation methods.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage should not be added around stacked appliances in a way that blocks access,
    airflow or maintenance.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the side gaps carefully</h2>
  <p>
    Narrow gaps beside washing machines can be useful, but only if they are genuinely
    accessible.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a slim trolley or gap organiser, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>gap width</li>
    <li>gap depth</li>
    <li>gap height</li>
    <li>skirting boards</li>
    <li>hose position</li>
    <li>tap position</li>
    <li>appliance movement</li>
    <li>whether the trolley can roll out fully</li>
    <li>whether the machine door or lid still opens</li>
    <li>whether the trolley becomes unstable when loaded</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A slim trolley may fit the visible gap but catch on hoses, skirting, taps or uneven
    flooring.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing heavy detergent bottles in narrow trolleys if the trolley becomes hard
    to move or unstable when full.
  </p>

  <h2>Check storage above the machine</h2>
  <p>
    The space above a washing machine can be useful, especially above a front loader.
  </p>
  <p>Possible options may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shelves</li>
    <li>baskets</li>
    <li>over-machine racks</li>
    <li>light laundry supplies</li>
    <li>towel storage</li>
    <li>detergent storage</li>
    <li>peg baskets</li>
    <li>cloth storage</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Before buying above-machine storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>reach height</li>
    <li>item weight</li>
    <li>wall fixing requirements</li>
    <li>machine movement</li>
    <li>top-loader lid clearance</li>
    <li>dryer clearance</li>
    <li>whether items could fall</li>
    <li>whether storage blocks taps or hoses</li>
    <li>whether the laundry is damp</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Heavy bottles should not be stored so high that they are difficult to lift down safely.
  </p>
  <p>
    For renters, wall-mounted shelves or fixed racks may not be suitable without approval.
    For rental-specific planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/renter-friendly-laundry-storage-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">
      Renter-Friendly Laundry Storage: What to Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep taps, hoses and power points accessible</h2>
  <p>
    Laundry storage should not block the parts of the appliance area that may need
    inspection or access.
  </p>
  <p>Keep clear access to:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>taps</li>
    <li>hoses</li>
    <li>power points</li>
    <li>vents</li>
    <li>filters if applicable</li>
    <li>drains</li>
    <li>appliance doors</li>
    <li>machine controls</li>
    <li>service panels</li>
    <li>the area behind or beside the machine where practical</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If a storage unit has to be fully dismantled before taps or hoses can be reached,
    it may not be suitable.
  </p>
  <p>
    The laundry may look more organised, but maintenance becomes harder.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep drying needs separate from appliance storage</h2>
  <p>
    It is easy to treat the washing machine and dryer area as the answer to every laundry
    problem.
  </p>
  <p>But drying space may need its own plan.</p>
  <p>Before adding storage around appliances, check whether the real issue is:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>wet clothes waiting for space</li>
    <li>drying racks blocking the room</li>
    <li>poor airflow</li>
    <li>towels taking too long to dry</li>
    <li>nowhere to store a folded airer</li>
    <li>a dryer area that is already crowded</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If drying is the main problem, focus on drying space before buying more appliance-area
    organisers.
  </p>
  <p>
    For drying-specific planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/laundry-drying-space-what-to-measure-before-buying-airers-or-racks/">
      Laundry Drying Space: What to Measure Before Buying Airers or Racks</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Store cleaning products carefully</h2>
  <p>
    Detergents, stain removers and sprays are often stored near the washing machine.
  </p>
  <p>Before adding shelves or baskets, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>bottle height</li>
    <li>whether products stand upright</li>
    <li>whether bottles leak</li>
    <li>whether products are near heat or moisture</li>
    <li>whether children or pets can reach them</li>
    <li>whether products are stored according to their labels</li>
    <li>whether heavy bottles are too high</li>
    <li>whether daily-use products are easy to reach</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Storage should make regular products easier to use and inspect.
  </p>
  <p>
    For more detail, see:
    <a href="/guides/cleaning-product-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-cabinets-or-caddies/">
      Cleaning Product Storage: What to Check Before Buying Cabinets or Caddies</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about under-tub and nearby storage first</h2>
  <p>
    Sometimes the best appliance-area storage is not directly around the machine.
  </p>
  <p>Nearby storage may work better, such as:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>under-tub baskets</li>
    <li>laundry caddies</li>
    <li>a shelf beside the tub</li>
    <li>a basket for cloths and gloves</li>
    <li>a compact hamper outside the appliance area</li>
    <li>a drying rack stored away from the machine</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the machine area is already tight, do not force storage into it.
  </p>
  <p>
    For under-tub planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/laundry-tub-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-under-sink-organisers/">
      Laundry Tub Storage: What to Check Before Buying Under-Sink Organisers</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Common washing machine and dryer storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>
    Appliance-area storage can go wrong when products are chosen before clearances are
    checked.
  </p>
  <p>Common mistakes include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying shelves that block a top-loader lid</li>
    <li>placing baskets in front of a front-loader door</li>
    <li>blocking dryer ventilation</li>
    <li>storing heavy bottles too high</li>
    <li>using a slim trolley that cannot roll out fully</li>
    <li>blocking taps, hoses or power points</li>
    <li>assuming stacked appliances do not need manufacturer guidance</li>
    <li>adding storage that makes cleaning behind machines harder</li>
    <li>ignoring appliance movement during use</li>
    <li>treating every gap as usable storage</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The goal is not to fill every space around the machines. The goal is to make the
    laundry easier to use while keeping appliance access clear.
  </p>

  <h2>When not to buy appliance-area storage yet</h2>
  <p>
    You may not need storage around the washing machine or dryer yet if the real issue is
    clutter or routine.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check whether the area contains:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>empty detergent bottles</li>
    <li>duplicate cleaning products</li>
    <li>baskets in the wrong place</li>
    <li>unused drying racks</li>
    <li>cloths or towels without a home</li>
    <li>products stored on the machine by habit</li>
    <li>items that belong under the tub or on a shelf</li>
    <li>old laundry supplies that can be removed</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If clearing the area improves access, a new organiser may not be needed.
  </p>
  <p>
    Sometimes the best improvement is keeping the machine area clear rather than adding
    more storage to it.
  </p>

  <h2>Simple washing machine and dryer space checklist</h2>
  <p>
    Before buying storage around a washing machine or dryer, check:
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Have I measured the machine width, depth and height?</li>
    <li>Does the washing machine door or lid open fully?</li>
    <li>Does the dryer door open fully?</li>
    <li>Are taps, hoses and power points accessible?</li>
    <li>Is dryer ventilation kept clear?</li>
    <li>Does the appliance manufacturer give placement or clearance guidance?</li>
    <li>Will storage block cleaning or maintenance access?</li>
    <li>Can a trolley or basket move without hitting hoses or doors?</li>
    <li>Are heavy bottles stored at a safe, reachable height?</li>
    <li>Does the storage suit a rental if needed?</li>
    <li>Is drying space the real problem?</li>
    <li>Would clearing clutter solve the issue first?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Washing machine and dryer storage works best when it respects the appliance space.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure carefully, keep access clear, follow manufacturer guidance, and choose storage
    that supports the laundry routine without crowding the machines.
  </p>

